metadata.name: Luminaries #47
metadata.description:
There is no light without dark.

Luminaries is a study in symmetry, contrast and flow, with a palette inspired by the twelve full moon names. Owning a Luminary enables you to request a signed print for an additional fee. 

You can learn more about features and prints at: https://www.phaust.art/luminary

Each Luminary is composed of moons in various phases. Their layout derived from a handful of geometries. They contrast with their surroundings: filled with glittering stars, inky strokes or solid colour. 

Backgrounds can split along lines of symmetry – with dark and light contrasting as strokes seamlessly flow across the two halves. 

Luminaries are alive. They’re in retrograde once a month, a day in which you’ll see yours in a new light.

------

Collection Size: 158. One for each of the confirmed moons in our solar system.

Palettes: 12 + 1. One for each of the full moons plus a rarer secret palette: Wolf, Snow, Worm, Pink, Flower, Strawberry, Buck, Sturgeon, Harvest, Hunter, Beaver, Cold, ????.

Retrograde: day of the month that your Luminary will change for one day only.

S: to save at high resolution. 

Prints: request from https://www.phaust.art/luminary

metadata.name: Morixels Colab #1 CryptoMask #11
metadata.description:
We all have a mask and we hide our real selves behind it
What mask do you have?

The CryptoMask is unique random Generated 200 PFP NFTs.
The number of Traits in this collection is 8 (86 layers) and it has the ability to make unique 102,453,120 NFTs.

To create balance, these NFTs are randomly minted, and this is a chance for everyone to get a rare version. So due to the low price of these NFTs, if the rare version did not belong to you, it is still possible for you to mint the new NFTs.

Because this is an NFT in PFP format, you can put it on your avatar on Twitter or Instagram.

This project is a collaboration project between Morteza Yousefi and Zahra Ghorbani and it is a Benefit for the owners of the most Morixels to Collaborate with Morixels Designer.

You can read more information on Morixels website 👇

Website: https://morixels.com/

by: @morteza_yousefy & @mo0n_zi

metadata.name: Before/After #191
metadata.description:
A visual representation of a non-linear transformation. Each line connects a data point before the transformation has been applied to its corresponding point after the transformation has been applied. Switch to debug mode to see the untransformed and transformed points. Outline mode shows only the lines and can be used for plotting. (Plotting will likely work best on outputs where the total number of lines is low.)

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive transformation (t-SNE) implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. The final artwork is a static SVG file that can be downloaded and displayed at any resolution. No external libraries have been used.

More information about this collection is provided here: https://clauswilke.com/art/project/before-after

I would like to thank Bartholomew Littlesilver for helpful artistic feedback, Liam Egan for help with creating plottable SVGs, and BRUTALISTI and neophob for encouraging me to pursue AssemblyScript for implementing performance-critical code.

Press 'm' to cycle between normal, debug, and outline mode.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Elementary Cellular Emoji Automata #932
metadata.description:
Features the full set of 1761 emojis, including skin tone and gender modifiers and all flags.
Arranged using the full 256 ruleset of one-dimensional cellular automata

If “random seed” is true then the seed of the generation is randomized using Math.random() meaning that the pattern will change on regeneration.
The ruleset, emoji, colors and all other properties will remain the same.

Auto-adjusts to screen size

Compatible with as many browsers and systems as possible

metadata.name: Sketch C #20
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch C has added a subtractive / destructive element to the simple grid from Sketches A and B. Colors are mostly the same, but more variation has been added to the outputs as well as the hue and saturation of the colors themselves. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

metadata.name: Disjoint and Disoriented #74
metadata.description:
Disjoint and Disoriented is about the abstract structure formed by the equalities and oppositions of its parts.

It might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop is recommended.

There are three render options available as url parameters in live mode:
- size=XXXX (up to 5760 pixels)
- texture=0 (disable canvas texture for print)
- shader=1 (use the shader throughout the painting process, can be heavy)

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi and lunarean, 2022.

metadata.name: Ribbonacci #203
metadata.description:
Interlocking ribbons are placed around focal points like sunflower seeds, using the Golden angle.

Features: six color schemes, two color variation types, three rendering styles, and variable aspect ratios.

----

The Golden angle is based on φ ("phi"), the most irrational number. Using this angle between successive ribbons means that as they spiral outwards, they end up distributed evenly around the center. The Golden angle is visible in many plants, not just the sunflower, since it helps prevent leaves from shading each other. ("Fibonacci phyllotaxis")

Phi, the Golden angle, and Fibonacci numbers generally have many fascinating, unexpected, and beautiful mathematical and geometric relationships. Learning about them was a delight.

----

Keys: 1-8 to change pixel density, s or double click to save, S to toggle drop shadows if present.
URL parameters: shadows (0 or 1), animated (0 or 1), aspect (e.g. 16:9, 2:3, 8.5:11)
